shared_text:
Clare High School Athletics
August 25 at 12:25 PM ·

ATHLETICS TRANSPORTATION GUIDELINES

These are in place for all athletic teams.

We will transport kids to games using school transportation. The following guidelines are a part of every road trip, beginning with golf today.

Busses will arrive 15 minutes prior to scheduled leave time so coaches can utilize the MHSAA COVID 19 checklists and temporal thermometers with their teams we do prior to every practice.

THE FOLLOWING APPLIES TO EVERY SCHOOL IN THE STATE--If a student-athlete has a fever higher than 100.4 prior to entering the bus, THEY WILL NOT BE ALLOWED TO TRAVEL. We ask for your understanding in this matter, as you certainly would likely not want your child playing a sport against another athlete with a fever. They will not be allowed to travel to the contest, and will need to be away from school and team until they have a "normal" temperature for at least 24 hours without medication.

Our coaches will be assigning seats to athletes on the bus trips.

Wesring masks is required on the bus.

shared_text:
Clare High School Athletics
July 21 at 8:37 AM ·

By this point, if your CHS son or daughter is interested in playing a fall sport, they should have been in contact with the respective Varsity coach (contact info on the CHS Athletics website). If they played a sport last year, they are not required to have a new physical IF they meet all of the requirements on the MHSAA Health Waiver, which all varsity coaches have. HOWEVER, we are STRONGLY encouraging all student-athletes to get a new physical if able.

At this time, all MHSAA fall sports are scheduled to begin "on time". This is subject to change and will be reliant on a number of things out of our control. Also, the next few weeks could also potentially see MHSAA-initiated changes to the calendar in terms of permissible team activities.

We ask for both your flexibility and understanding as we embark on an unprecedented school year together.

RRNSports.com
March 17 at 11:35 PM ·

The Michigan High School Athletic Association has NOT cancelled the spring sports seasons. In fact, the MHSAA has not even officially cancelled the basketball and hockey tournaments. Those were put on hold last Thursday until April 5, and the status has not changed. The only announcement from the Association came on Tuesday that “In doing our part to keep everyone as safe as possible, MHSAA staff is working remotely as of March 17. The MHSAA headquarters is currently closed to visitors and walk-in customers.”

Clare Public Schools
March 16 at 10:26 AM ·

Good morning Pioneers -

This message will follow in an all-call.

CPS and Chartwells Food Service are working on assisting families by providing meals to children up to age 18 (age 26 with disability). We are offering two meals per child per day for 3-4 days at a time, available for pickup on Thursdays and Mondays, beginning March 19th, 2020.

Parents will be able to pick up meals in the loop east of the middle school gym curbside (no entry into the building, no need to exit your car). Pickup will be available from 4-6 p.m. on these days.

In order that we plan effectively for the right amount of food and staff on hand to prepare, please call 989.386.1258 as soon as is possible to request the service (for accurate counting purposes only...there is no charge to families).

Our goal is to feed kids. No ID is required to pick up meals, they are free to all children.

Thank you in advance.

March 13 at 10:52 AM ·

With the Clare Public Schools being closed for the next three weeks, the program will continue to provide food for you and your family.

Food bag pick up will be at the Clare United Methodist Church office on Thursdays (March 19, March 26 and April 2) from 1:00 pm - 5:30 pm.

At this time, you will not need to return the backpack as usual. A bag of food will be ready for pickup. If there is a need prior to next Thursday, please reach out and we’ll do our best to assist.

Congrats to our girls and boys ski teams....from Coach Gariglio

So Proud of both these teams! After losing 6 seniors last year both teams captured both conference titles tonight. The boys lost the first 2 races to a really good Mt Pleasant team, but they fought back and won the last three! Both teams peeked at the right time and so many improvements over the last 3 weeks. The girls' team was very solid this year and both teams are returning a lot of skiers next season. Proud to be a Pioneer!

Winter Sports Update:

Wrestling competes in the team regional at Chippewa Hills High School on Wednesday, February 12th at 5:30 p.m. against Big Rapids.

Boys Basketball stands currently at 8-3, tied for 3rd in the JPC with Shepherd on deck tomorrow at home.

Girls Basketball stands at 11-1, leading the JPC, and traveling to Shepherd this evening.

Girls Bowling is undefeated in JPC league action. Jenna Bets has the high league average at 179, and Sofiah Coker has the 3rd highest league average.

Boys bowling has already surpassed last year's win total in the JPC.

Girls skiing is currently in 1st place in the conference, and all are performing well.

Boys skiing is currently in 2nd place, needing a win in our next meet at the conference championship to claim the crown.

It's a great time to get out and watch our student-athletes compete!

Congratulations to the following Pioneers from the class of 2020, signing on to continue their careers as student-athletes at the college level:

Kameron Haag -- Track/Cross Country at Northwood
Brooklyn Tocco -- Softball at Delta College
Gwen Sherwood -- Soccer at Alderson-Broaddus University
Jenna Betts -- Bowling at Marian University

These Pioneers will continue to represent Clare well in all they do.

In other athletic highlights, the Girls Varsity Basketball team sits at 11-1 and currently leads the Jack Pine Conference.

We host our Boys Basketball District tournament from March 2nd-6th, and a Division 4 Girls Quarterfinal game on March 17th.

Clare is a great place to live, learn, and achieve!

Tim Packard‎Clare High School Wrestling
February 18, 2019 at 12:53 PM ·

3 Pioneers are moving on to the Individual State Finals at Ford Field on March 1st & 2nd.
At 125 Senior Kyle Schaaf hopes to improve on last years runner up finish, Schaaf is 45-4 on the year and this is his 4th time qualifying for state.
At 135 Sophomore Jon Bouchey will make his first appearance at state with a 41-11 record.
AT 140 Junior Colt Smedley has qualified for the 2nd year in a row. Smedley is 43-4 on the year.

Congrats to the rest of the kids competing for Clare this past Saturday, you had a great season! Blake white, Brady Fruge', Devin Gaskill & Josh Williams.

image:
Clare Pioneer Volleyball
October 26, 2018 at 10:33 AM ·

2018 Seniors!
These four seniors were part of the group that I coached when I first started coaching at Clare!

I have seen them grow into AMAZING young women.

They have grown as volleyball players, but more importantly as young women.

They have been a part of fundraising, organizing events, team camps, youth camps, public speaking, raising awareness for mental health and breast cancer, and helping to grow a program that we all are so proud to be a part of.

Thank you Kennedy, Jayce, Kylie, and Rease for letting me be a small part of your journey through Middle School and High School athletics. I cannot wait to see where life takes you and the ways that you change the world and make it a better place!

NOW ON TO BOYNE CITY AND DISTRICTS!!

Clare Pioneer Volleyball updated their cover photo.
October 11, 2018 at 8:44 AM ·

Since August 8th these young ladies have been in the gym working hard to be successful on the court and they have had done that on MANY occasions!

More importantly they have been working hard at finding ways to help with mental health awareness. October is the kickoff for our Be the Change campaign. We will spend the month (and the rest of the school year) finding small ways to make a difference here at Clare Public Schools.

This morning the girls wrote over 500 inspiration messages to put on each students locker in the high school with a "Kindness is Always in Style" magnet.

Our locker room was full of smiles, laughter, and team work this morning as they were trying to make a small difference in someones day! What a way to start the day!
#kindnessIsAlwaysInStyle

post_text:
Boys' Track
Congrats to the boys’ track team for sweeping Harrison and Gladwin at Harrison, and once again finishing out the regular undefeated.

The Pioneers won many events and set many PRs across the board.

The 3200, 800, and 400 relays were victorious. Joel Lingaur set a new PR in the Pole Vault; Tyler smith won the high jump with a new PR; Dustin VanSicklen won the shot with a new PR; Noah Nivison won the discus; Kaleb Brewer and Brecken Corp PR’d in the 110’s; Justin Tickle won the 800; JJ Gross, Brody Albee, Trent Cook, and Ben Wood PR’d in the 400; Colt Smedley PR’d in his win of the 200; Atreyu Franks PR’d in the 100; Kyle Yost and Tiernan Gallagher PR’d in the discus; and Cristian Kunse PR’d in the shot put and discus.

The Pioneers next compete at the Oiler Invite tomorrow in Mt Pleasant.

post_text: The girls' track team ran well at the Shepherd Invitational on Friday night, landing 4th in the big school division. There were many strong performances on the night. Lainey Veenkant ran 11:00, Katherine Haupt ran 12:06, Kameron Haag 12:07, and Olivia Haring 12:27- which are very impressive times for the 3200m Run. Division medalists included: Grace Gomez clearing a new pr of 8'8" to finish 2nd in the pole vault, Lexi LaPoe-1st in 300m hurdles, Jenna Betts tied for 2nd in high jump with a season PR of 4'7", Erin Weeks finished 6th in long jump, Lainey Veenkant 4th in the 2 mile, Kayden Barber 4th in the 100m Hurdles, Olivia Cook 6th in the 100m dash, Riley Schroeder 4th in 400m Dash, the 400m relay and 800m relay finished 1st in their division, and the 1600m relay team finished 3rd. Great job ladies- keep working hard and keep getting better every day!

post_text:
Boys' Track
Congrats to the boys' track team for winning the Shepherd Blue Jay Invite's large school division on Friday. Medalists on the day were as follows: Colts Smedley, 5th with a new PR in the 100; Xavier Martin, 1st in the 200; Justin Tickle, 5th in the 400; David Good, 2nd with a new PR in the 3200; Kolt Lincoln and Myles Williamson, 3rd and 4th in the 110's; Lincoln and Williamson, 3rd and 5th in the 300's; Kaleb Brewer, 6th with a new PR in the 300's; the 400 and 800 relays teams were first; the 1600 relay was second; the 3200 relay was third; Tad Matiza, 5th in the long jump; Alec Hoffman, 5th with a new PR in the pole vault; Tyler Smith, 5th in the high jump; Noah Nivison and Zac Stickler, 1st and 2nd in the discus; Jack Moore, 5th in the shot put; and Zac Stickler claimed the shot put by re-setting his own school record with a toss of 56-1.5. The Pioneers wrap up the regular season against Gladwin and Harrison in Harrison on Wednesday. Great job, guys.

Congrats to the boys' track team by landing two commanding wins against Whittemore-Prescott and Ogemaw Heights yesterday at home. Many PR's and state-leading performances were posted on a rare good-weather day this spring.

Zac Stickler won the shot and discus; Tyler Smith won the high jump; Tad Matiza won the long jump, and Alec Hoffman won the pole vault to round out an early lead in all field events. Xavier Martin and Brenden Sersaw posted two of the fastest times in the state in the 100, then teamed up with JJ Gross and Colt Smedley to post the fastest time in the state in the 800 relay. Martin, Smedley, Drew Schuster, and Jake Hawley would later team up to post the fastest time in the… More

post_text: The girls track team kicked off their season with wins against Ogemaw Heights and Whittemore Prescott. The Pioneers won 13 of 17 events on the day. There were many great performances across the board to continue to build on. Event winners on the day included: 200m- Ellie Johnson, 1600m and 800m- Lainey Veenkant, 3200m- Bri Smith, 100m Hurdles and 300m Hurdles- Lexi Lapoe, High Jump- Jenna Betts, Pole Vault- Grace Gomez, Discus- Natalee Kunse, and all four relays (4x1, 4x2, 4x4, and 4x4). Other shout outs go out to Gwen Sherwood in the 100m dash, Madisen McNeilly in the 200m and 400m, Hayley Campbell and Zoey Blanchard in the 200m, Bailey Taylor in the 100m hurdles and pole vault, Josie Fox in pole vault, Molly Weeks in high jump, McKenzie Grant in shot put, and Kennedy Blackburn in discus. Great job ladies! Meet at the track today after school for practice/home middle school track meet today!
